Yes, there is no way around this. Life is not always easy and especially right now this may be hard. However, I’m going to tell you all what I always tell my first graders. This is hard, but “You CAN do hard things” and we are here with you ever step of the way. We are Comfrey strong!

Sending all of my love to you,
Mrs. Herrig

post_text:
Just in case you're wondering what goes on during a day of distance learning...this is what a kindergarten day "typically" looks like...even though "typical" is currently a little difficult to define!

Every morning I meet one-on-one with students on Google Hangouts to individualize instruction in reading (vocabulary, books, phonics-short vowel blending) and math (adding and subtracting, calendar concepts, number recognition, even and odd, geometry, graphing, time and money). I check in with writing and literacy components, and most important - talk about how their life is going. We also meet as a group in the afternoon to do group activities - virtual field trips, games, listening to a story, music, sharing, our Goodbye Song, etc. The kids all check in during the day to show me what they've accomplished and at times just to chat! My kindergarten parents/guardians have been incredible - I couldn't make this work without help from home!

Minnesota Department of Education
March 31 at 11:00 AM ·

Schools had just eight days to plan for distance learning. It is a challenge our schools have never faced before. We’re incredibly proud of the dedication our schools have shown to their communities and the innovation they’ve displayed in meeting this task. While the way we educate is different, the education is the same. We are committed to providing a high-quality education to every student, no matter the format. We ask that parents continue to be patient as we all learn to embrace this new normal together.

post_text: I know this is about athletes, but a good message for all our students
shared_text:
Proactive Coaching
September 14, 2019 at 9:30 AM ·

We say this all the time to individuals who call or message us describing a tough situation with a coach, parent, team or teammate, so we may as well just say it to everyone -
But the bottom line is, every “bad situation” is an opportunity for growth for the young athlete and a dress rehearsal for real life. This is not the last time they are going to have to deal with a difficult person, a confidence cutter, be in a situation that they don’t think is fair, etc…. and so we encourage parents to listen with positive intent, help prepare them to deal with it and turn it into a life lesson. Be thankful that these “opportunities” are happening to them while they are young and have you walking along side them.
